issue_body:
The landing page shows this signature at one point:

     void gladLoadGLLoader(GLADloadproc);

But in my generated glad.h for 4.6 I find this:

     GLAPI int gladLoadGLLoader(GLADloadproc);

Looking in the implementation in glad.c I get the idea this fctn is supposed to return true on success, but it returns false for me, and yet things seem to work (I would sort of expect everything to fail if that fctn does).  So I'm not sure what's going on exactly, could be my error for sure.

It should be possible for other projects to define a conversion to `gmpy2` types. As is typically done in Python, this could be done by a `__mpz__` method. That is, the function `mpz` should do something like (assuming also #124):

``` python
def mpz(x):
    # Existing code
    if isinstance(x, known_types):
        return known_conversion_to_mpz(x)

    # New code
    try:
        m = x.__mpz__
    except AttributeError:
        pass
    else:
        return m()
    try:
        x = int(x)
    except TypeError:
        pass
    else:
        return known_conversion_to_mpz(x)

    # Existing code
    raise TypeError("mpz() requires numeric or string argument")
```

Three particular cases of the Lexogen SIRV synthetic RNA spike in (ground truth, so every mapping junction has the correct answer) have different - and now incorrect - mapped junctions after switching from an older version of minimap2 (v.2.1.1) to the newest one (v.2.7).

The three sequences are here: https://www.dropbox.com/s/l5mue20tnavvwf6/missing_in_new.fa?dl=0

They should belong to SIRV304, SIRV403, and SIRV408, respectively. Based on BLASR mapping back to the reference transcript [blasr file](https://www.dropbox.com/s/kpa4ny2s5nw8uy8/missing_in_new.fa.blasr?dl=0), the accuracy for the three sequences are 98% (12 ins 1 del), 99% (1 insertion), and 100%. The errors are actually of no consequence here, because even when I take SIRV304, SIRV403, and SIRV408 [fasta file here](https://www.dropbox.com/s/bl2jsn9xu4wlj95/test.fa?dl=0) with no error, they still map incorrectly. In comparison, GMAP and an earlier version of minimap2 (v2.1.1.) both mapped the sequences correctly, so this seems to be a case of algorithmic differences.

Below I show the junction differences between the old minimap2 (which are the correct answers) vs the new minimap2. 

**For SIRV304**, the 5th and 6th exon have a different junction, shifted by 4 and 11 bp respectively.

